content.location: Just left of other unknown route on east face

content.description: Start on slopes ledge to good ledge
content.location: Just left of v3 on east arete

content.description: In the chimney crack between the Jabberwock boulders. Face the slab section with the overhang pressing against your back. Use a tight squeeze, backpress, and jug hold to reach the top.
content.location: Jabberwock boulder, around the corner from Jabberwocky.

content.description: Start with hands matched on a low ledge.  Climb straight up on good side pulls and crimps.  Lots of options for hands and feet.  Easy, juggy topout.
content.protection: Pads and spotter.  The landing is nice and flat, but a trip or stumble after landing could send you into a small boulder nearby.
content.location: Starts on the north side of the Jabberwock boulder.  Start on the low lip to the right of the pod where Jabberwock starts.

content.description: Sit start up slopes on scene.
content.location: East face sit start by arete.

content.description: An easier variation of Jabberwock arete that utilizes the better edges higher up to bypass the crux sequence for the finish. Sit start on jug far right and traverse left. Finish by exiting the hole feet first
content.location: Low hold far right of the boulder

content.description: Not sure if anyone has already climbed this, but it was fun, nonetheless. Start on the same hold as Jabberwocky (V4) but got straight up on decent holds that disappear to an easier slab finish.
content.location: Same start as the mail slot jug start for jabberwocky.

content.description: Sit-start in the big pod. Traverse left on edges until you can shove your legs into the big hole and wiggle through.
content.location: The Jabberwock boulder is passed when walking towards the Monkey Boy Boulder from the Teepee area. It will be on the right side of the trail maybe 200 feet before reaching Monkey Boy. This problem is on the north side of the boulder.

content.description: Start on right side in undercling move left until you pass through small hole on right side for top out. If you have large shoulders  this may be difficult to fit. After putting both feet in the hole some find it acceptable to top out straight up from the hole.
content.location: Find obvious hole to pass through then start on right at large underling.

content.description: There was no chalk at all on this one, but it was clearly brushed at some point. Anyone know the FA? It is now cleaned up and ready to go. Not sure how this fell out of favor as it's a quality problem. Sit start with right hand in pocket, left on vertical edge. Climb up and use both aretes.
content.location: East side of the Jabberwock boulder.

content.description:
Follows the first moves of Jabberwock arete, then diverges straight up the face father than traversing left toward the hole in the rock.

In other words, start with an undercling in a pod and fire up for a good crimp.  Then bear slightly left and then straight up the face of the bolder.
content.location: North side of the Jabberwock Boulder.  Starts in a pod on the underside of the north face--same as Jabberwock Arete.

content.description: Sit start at south arete go around corner  to left then top out.
